386→                        <div id="content">Let $\epsilon&#62;0$ and $\omega(n)$ count the number of distinct prime factors of $n$. Are there infinitely many values of $n$ such that\[\omega(n-k) &#60; (1+\epsilon)\frac{\log k}{\log\log k}\]for all $k&#60;n$ which are sufficiently large depending on $\epsilon$ only?<br><br>Can one show the stronger version with\[\omega(n-k) &#60; \frac{\log k}{\log\log k}+O(1)\]is false?</div>
