408→                           One can ask similar questions for $\Omega$, the number of prime factors with multiplicity, where $\log k/\log\log k$ is replaced by $\log_2k$.<br><br>See also <a href="/248" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[248]</a> and <a href="/413" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer ugc" target="_blank">[413]</a>.<br><br>In the comments DottedCalculator has disproved the second stronger version, proving that in fact for all large $n$ there exists $k&lt;n$ such that\[\omega(n-k)\geq \frac{\log k}{\log\log k} + c\frac{\log k}{(\log\log k)^2}\]for some constant $c&gt;0$.
